This is what a Suicide Survivor looks like. 

Today marks 12 years since I planned to take my life at the age of 15 on December 23, 2010. Each year, I remember this date as the most significant day in my year- I call it my Rebirth Day. It reminds me of all I’ve been through and all I’ve accomplished since that day. It reminds me that my life is still worth it. 

This is what a Suicide Survivor looks like. Here’s why that’s important: 

* I often get told I “don’t look like someone who struggled with depression and suicide ideation.” Stereotypes in our world continue to push a narrative that suicide only impacts certain people or looks a certain way. This is untrue. Suicide does not discriminate and everybody shows different signs. I can’t even count how many survivors have come up to me and said, “I’ve never told anybody, but me too.” All different people, different backgrounds, cultures, and ethnicities. 

* Many people think suicide ideation, attempts, and deaths are uncommon. The data disproves that: we lose 800,000 people to suicide worldwide every year, one person every 11.5 minutes in the US, and nearly 1.2 million attempts in the nation. Suicide is more common than you think. 

12 years later, and I am blessed to be the President of @lifeisworthitorg and the Youth Suicide Prevention Coordinator for the Nevada Office of Suicide Prevention. I am even more grateful that 12 years ago, my parents intervened and connected me to life saving help and education. It is my mission now to continue advocating for mental health and educating youth and their communities to prevent suicide. 

We’ve recently seen several high profile suicide deaths in the media. Sadly, each day we lose approximately 125 people in the US to suicide. These people are our friends, family members, neighbors, coworkers, and loved ones. Please don’t wait until the next high profile suicide death to take it seriously. You can prevent suicide by educating yourself on the signs and safe language on suicide, learning how to ask life saving questions, and connecting a person to care. If you don’t know where to start, send me a message and let’s chat. 🤍 #itsnotokbutitwillbe
When Audrey Hepburn said, “I am not a one in a million kind of girl, I am a once in a lifetime kind of woman…” I felt that. 🖤

Thank you to my friends and family who helped celebrate with me last night and all who continue to support me. 🤍

Thank you to everyone who came to the @lifeisworthitorg Launch + Open House Event on May 25th! I’m just getting around to posting because the response has been tremendous, but I’m incredibly grateful for everyone who continues to support us. 

For those who don’t know, I am the Founder and President of @lifeisworthitorg. I launched the organization in 2020 with one mission: to provide hope and resources for young people struggling with their mental health. Fast forward to 2023, and we have grown to providing programs, workshops, and curriculum to educate youth and their communities on total life health and wellness to help prevent suicide. We are so excited to continue this journey and provide education to all youth so they can live the healthiest lives they can. 🤍

Content Warning: Suicide 

Today begins Suicide Prevention Month and although preventing suicide is every month for me, I’m grateful there’s an emphasis on prevention during September of each year. Preventing suicide is everybody’s business. 

Here’s some reasons why: 

* We lose someone in the U.S. to suicide every 11 minutes.
* 80% of suicides are by males, but females attempt 3x more.
* 1.7 million people attempted suicide in the U.S. last year. This number reflects reported attempts- we know there are more unreported. 
* Suicide kills more veterans, police officers, firefighters, and first responders every year than in the line of duty. 
* Suicide is the 2nd leading cause of death for youth aged 10-24. 
* Suicide doesn’t discriminate- it impacts anybody from any walk of life, culture, demographic, etc. 

In 2010, I was 15 years old struggling with depression and anxiety which led me to make a plan to end my life. We don’t always know what people are struggling with based on what they look like externally. I share the second photo, which is the most important photo I have, that shows me 5 days before I planned to take my life. I went to a holiday party that night with friends. I had lost 30 pounds in a month and was 105 pounds because my sadness prevented me from eating. Nobody knew. I’m thankful my attempt was interrupted and that I’m here today. 

This September, I’ll be traveling the West Coast providing trainings, presenting at conferences, speaking at events, and joining podcasts talking about suicide prevention. And I’m not alone. Hundreds of advocates and survivors will join me across the country and world doing the same thing because we cannot do it alone. This September, I encourage you to learn about the signs, don’t be afraid to ask about suicide, and get people connected to resources, because you can save a life by doing so. 

If you or someone you know is struggling, call or text 988- #1 for Veterans, #2 for Spanish, #3 for LGBTQ+.

Content Warning // Suicide

Celebrating 13 years of rebirth today 🤍 

Every December 23rd is an important reminder to me of how special life is and how far I’ve come since planning to end my life in 2010, to now helping other people find hope in the midst of their struggles. I can’t believe it’s been 13 years and with each year, I find more purpose and passion. I’m proud to say this year I’ve trained over 2,000 people in suicide prevention through classes, presentations, workshops, and conferences with so much more to come with @lifeisworthitorg and @itwillbepodcast 

Thank you to everyone who sends me messages about your own stories and for the support I’ve received along this journey. If you’re wondering what you can do to prevent suicide, I encourage you to check in with your friends and family members especially during this time, as the holidays can be so hard for many people. If you or someone you know is in a mental health crisis, you can call or text 988. 🤍
Blue Christmas 💙
